North Korea rejects unilateral disarmament with no confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the UN on Saturday that maintaining sanctions was heightening the country's mistrust of the United States, which in such circumstances would absolutely refuse to unilaterally renounce its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho said on the occasion of the General Assembly of the world body that North Korea took "important measures of goodwill" during the past year, such as the halt to nuclear and missile tests, the dismantling of the nuclear test site and the commitment to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we do not see any consistent response from the United States," he said.
"Without trust in the United States, there will be no security in our national security and in such circumstances we absolutely refuse to disarm unilaterally first."
Although Ri has reused notes of complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” denuclearization by which North Korea would be rewarded on the basis of gradual actions, his statement was important because he did not entirely reject unilateral denuclearization as already done by Pyongyang in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump during the first absolute meeting between a US president in office and a North Korean leader, held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work towards “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula” while Trump promised guarantees to North Korea’s security.
North Korea sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States said Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also opposed calls to loosen the tough international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
"The United States insists on the need to 'have denuclearization first' and increase the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve their purpose in a coercive way and even opposes the 'end of war declaration,'" Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions can put us on our knees is an illusion of those who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that the continuation of sanctions is increasing our mistrust.”
Ri did not refer to programs of a second meeting between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader announced at the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the minister stressed the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: “If the counterpart to this denuclearization issue were South Korea and not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be dead at this point.”
But even so, the tone of Ri’s speech was significantly different from last year’s speech at the UN General Assembly, when he stated that it was inevitable to target U.S. territory with North Korea’s missiles after “the president of evil” Trump called Kim a “missile man” engaged in a suicide mission.
Before the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to “completely destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to embark on the path of disarmament, but said much still needs to be done and that sanctions will remain in place until North Korea’s denuclearization.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not have a deadline, stating that “whether it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia say the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: “Compliance with the Security Council sanctions must continue with force and without exception until complete, final and verified denuclearization is achieved.”
The Security Council unanimously supported the control sanctions against North Korea in 2006 in an attempt to stifle funding for nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again the following month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but the last trip did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July claiming that progress had been made, but a few hours later North Korea accused him of making "gangster requests."
North Korea had pledged during a meeting this month with Moon to dismantle a missile site and a nuclear complex if the U.S. had taken “compliant measures.”
He said Kim had explained to him that the “compliant measures” he wanted were security assurances Trump had committed to in Singapore and actions toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has pushed all of its students to sleep more in an attempt to counteract the growing male culture of studying for whole nights powered by caffeine.
One university scholar found that students at the number one university in the world often have no idea of the basic concepts of caring for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women’s Hospital, developed the course, which he believes to be the first of its kind in the United States.
He had the idea to start the course after a conference he had given on the impact of lack of sleep on learning.
“In the end, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why is this only being told to me now, when I’m in the last year?’
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me very much,” she told The Telegraph.
The course, taught for the first time this year, explains to students the essential concepts of how good sleep-related habits can help academic and athletic performance, as well as improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and general director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after finding that students suffered from a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive activities.
In one section there is the image of a bedroom, where students can select cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers and books to get to know the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep, and the importance of an evening routine.
In another section, participants are explained how long-term lack of sleep can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that it will not immediately change the behavior of students.
But we believe that they have the right to know, just as you have the right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes,” added Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of pride tied to the “white night to study” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students lead to a lack of sleep being an ever-growing problem.
Sleeping enough and with good quality sleep should be the students' "secret weapon" to fight stress, fatigue, anxiety, explained and even should serve to avoid obesity as lack of sleep brings the brain into a sleepless mode, making people constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student enrolled in the faculty of chemistry and physics biology, helped Professor Czeisler develop the course, after taking one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He explained that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a course aimed at the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, will be to ask all graduate students to follow a similar program of study before enrolling in this competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler advised students to set an alarm clock for when they need to go to bed, as well as for when they need to wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can tilt the circadian rhythm, leading to sleep problems.
