Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert really a genuine way to persuade people to ask for a call to action, or is it just another example of so-called “cliktivism”—people who feel like they’re really making a difference simply by signing a petition online or tweeting?
Since 2011, Global Citizen claims to have registered more than 19 million “actions” of its supporters, working for a bunch of different purposes.
It states that these actions have helped to urge world leaders to announce commitments and policies worth more than $37 billion, aimed at affecting the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
