Europe regained the trophy when the team of Danish captain Thomas Bjorn reached the 14.5 points needed to defeat the United States.
U.S. champion Phil Mickelson, who fought for most of the tournament, threw his tee shot in the water at the 16th hole of par 3 granting victory to Francesco Molinari.
The Italian golfer has distinguished himself in all his rounds by becoming one of four players ever to record a 5-0-0 since the tournament with the current formula was first played in 1979.
The American Jordan Spieth was defeated by the score of 5&4 by the lower Danish player Thorbjorn Olesen in the European team rankings.
The best player in the world, Dustin Johnson, has surrendered for 2&1 to Englishman Ian Poulter who may have played his last Ryder Cup.
A Ryder Cup veteran, Spanish Sergio Garcia, who has played eight, has become the European player who has won the most in the history of the tournament with 25.5 points.
