Red tide update: concentration decreases in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decrease in the concentration of red tide in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, spotted flowering conditions, which suggest a decrease in concentration, are evident in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties.
The red tide bloom extends about 130 miles off the coast from the north of Pinellas County to the south of Lee County.
The spots are located about 10 miles off Hillsborough County but in fewer areas than last week.
The red tide has also been observed in the county of Pasco.
Last week there was reported an average concentration in the county of Pinellas or off its coasts, a concentration from low to high off the county of Hillsborough, from a bottom concentration to a high concentration in the county of Manatee, from a bottom concentration to a high concentration in the county of Sarasota or off its coasts.
Cases of respiratory irritation continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No cases were reported last week in northwest Florida.
